  "method": [
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Bring a saucepan filled with water to the boil. Once boiling add the spinach leaves and blanch for 30 seconds, stirring regularly. Remove the spinach and transfer to a bowl of ice cold water. Set aside."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "To the same pan of water, add the beansprouts and blanch for 2 mins. Remove and set aside. Turn the heat off and set the pan and water aside to cook the noodles in later."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "For the pork mince: finely mince the garlic clove and spring onion, separating the whites and greens. Heat a glug of sesame oil in a saucepan over a high heat for about a minute. Add the pork mince and fry for about 3 mins until browned, breaking the mince into small pieces with a spoon as you go. Add the doubanjiang, light soy sauce, white sugar, MSG, minced garlic, the spring onion whites and a pinch of salt and black pepper. Fry for a further 1-2 mins. Transfer everything to a bowl and set aside."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "For the broth: to the same pan, add the chicken stock, oat milk, light soy sauce, mirin, MSG and a pinch of salt and black pepper. Bring to a boil over a high heat with the lid off. Simmer for 5 mins or until reduced by a quarter. Add the chilli oil and reduce the heat to lowest, set aside while we cook the noodles. Season to taste (it should be slightly overly salty)."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Bring the pot of water used to cook the spinach back to a boil. Once boiling, cook the noodles a minute shy of the pack instructions, then drain and divide between bowls."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Ladle the broth over the noodles so they’re submerged. Add a handful of beansprouts and top them with a large spoonful of pork mince, then serve some spinach and the spring onion greens on the side."
    }
  ],
